The Port Harcourt Electricity Distribution Company (PHED) said it  would soon embark on an aggressive metering of consumers in Akwa Ibom State to ensure that estimated billing scheme was reduced. Acting head, commercial, of (PHED) Akwa Ibom zone, Vincent Edewor,  who made this known  yesterday at a one-day public consultation on extraordinary tariff review under the multi-year tariff order in Uyo, explained  that  so far the company has  distributed over 100,000 prepaid meters to consumers in the state. At the forum, most  consumers raised concerns over the time of the proposed increase in the electricity tariff saying it would worsen the economic hardship they are facing given the ‘crazy bills’ currently being charged. They decried the estimated billing system, the irregular power supply, and poor services by the distribution company, saying that the forum should be used to feel the pulse of the consumers rather than seeking the approval of the consumers over a decision that might have already been taken. George Ibe and Clifford Thomas,  human right activists who spoke during the consultation among others urged the distribution company to postpone the planned tariff review until further consultations have been made with the consumers across the state. “We will be further burdened by the proposed increase, as we provide most of the power infrastructure such as electric pole , cables and other accessories  without  getting  refund  from  the distribution company,” said Thomas, a lawyer who also runs a Non-Governmental Organisation. John Onyi, manager corporate communications of PHED in his remarks said the planned tariff review when commenced would aid network expansion and rehabilitation, improve customer satisfaction, reduce complaints, increase power availability and elimination of estimated bill. He added that the proposed tariff review which takes effect from April 1, 2020 under the Multi-Year Tariff Order is in line with the directive of Nigerian Electricity Regulatory Commission.